		<div id="post_message_1459229"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>
					Originally Posted by <strong>Remfin</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1459216#post1459216" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost.gif" border="0" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">No, an actual nationalization would hurt banksters (or at least the general class of them, maybe not the specific people who caused the problem here). What we are going through is distinctively NOT nationalization, and we are suffering for it.<br />
<br />
Nationalization is probably the most free-market-ish thing we can do right now (short of letting everything just crash, which no one wants to do). But Americans have this stupid idea that nationalization = socialism when nationalization is just an action, and socialism is motivation. So instead we do what the American people think of as not-socialism (keep the government from owning the banks while not letting them crash), but in reality it is pure corporate socialism.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>You sound like Krugman.. <br />
<br />
<a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/23/opinion/23krugman.html" target="_blank">http://www.nytimes.com/2009/02/23/op...23krugman.html</a><br />
<br />
maybe Nationalization is the thing to do, or equitable?<br />
<br />
or maybe like this response got... 'A POX on all their(banksers) houses'<br />
<br />
is probably the general sentiment. <br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				Dr. Krugman, speak for yourself. &quot;So do we all&quot; &quot;believe&quot; &quot;'that a privately held banking system is the correct way to go'&quot; does not apply to all of us. Rather, it applies to old-style capitalists, who think that a little solder here, a dab of glue there, a patch on one corner, and a new leg on the other will suffice to prop up the upset applecart. Those days are gone. The total size of the problem is at least $10 trillion at this point, and that's not even counting factor X: derivatives and other exotic financial 'instruments' to be reckoned with.<br />
<br />
And then there is factor Y: credit card debt. When I mentioned this to my Citi banker on Friday her eyes rolled and she visibly winced. &quot;That&#146;s the biggest of all, and they're not talking about it at all.&quot; I doubt it's the biggest of all, but huge would be an understatement. When those who've lost their jobs -- perhaps their homes as well -- have a choice between paying down the CC balance and eating, we all know what they'll do. I mentioned to my banker that people are already getting letters saying that their interest rates have been jumped from 9 percent to 29 percent and may go higher. She said this is not possible, that they must have missed a payment or been late. I assured her this is not the case; rather, it's the giant gorilla in the middle of the room that's doing what he wants because he can. She promised to google my claim, she was so amazed -- and she a banker. Back to Mr. Rich's op/ed on denial on Sunday.<br />
<br />
What a new capitalism is: that's what we need to discuss, along with some reasonable interim laws to moderate the crisis. For openers, how about a freeze on CC rates at something like three points over prime, capped at 10 percent for a specified period of time? How about some discussion of how existing shareholders will NOT lose everything, but rather they'll be diluted and have to wait patiently along with the public/government to see their shares rise again? How about a way for the public to begin buying into the equity of the banks after stability/viability is reestablished? Or before if they can accept the risk. The same could be done for bank employees. In other words, let&#146;s develop a system that raises equity capital as much as possible &#150; not borrowed capital -- leading to eventual phase out of borrowed capital from the entire capitalist system, except for very short-term paper, bridge loans, and perhaps convertible preferred shares.<br />
<br />
Banks too-large-to-fail are also too-large-to-exist. This goes for many other corporations, as we see with the auto makers. The 'new capitalism' needs to deal with these behemoths, not start-ups, local banks, and others accountable to shareholders and the community. At the top of the 'new capitalism' list has to be the concept that too-large-to-fail makes an entity essentially a monopoly, which needs to be treated like a public utility, with regulated returns and leverage limited to acceptable limits and instruments. More rattling on about 'zombie' and 'bad' banks is useful, but also tends to anger the public and lead to 'a plague on all houses' convictions. We're stuck with a banking system, so let's try to figure out how to make it equitable, starting with curbing interest rates on credit cards and other consumer debt. And nationalize the Fed while we're at it.<br />
<br />
— Butler Crittenden, San Francisco, CA
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>as far as I can tell, Obama is failing because he keeps listening to the scum who created this mess.</div>
