		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_1459266"><div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px; ">
	<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px">Quote:</div>
	<table cellpadding="6" cellspacing="0" border="0" width="100%">
	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>
					Originally Posted by <strong>kaisann</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1459235#post1459235" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost.gif" border="0" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">As to returning control, the government could presumably allow Citibank to buy-back its stock at some future date. Many who were critical of the bank bailout complained on the grounds that the government was committing funds but not demanding voting shares as an investor like Warren Buffet would do.</div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>Possibly, but it’s a criticism without a context.  The all important question is what the Government does with its control.  It’s not as if the problems go away the moment the Government takes control.  The Treasury Secretary doesn’t exactly inspire confidence the that he knows how to fix the potential insolvency and toxic asset problem, nor does the President.  My great fear is that the Democrats will wield their control with the aim of political advantage rather than financial solvency considerations.  <br />
<br />
There are several actions they could take which would compound the banks current problems, with the bank acting as an intermediary, but de facto instrument of government special interest spending.  If all money is coming from the treasury, and government is calling the shots, then the government has just taken control of the economy and social policy to an unprecedented extent, with none of the safeguards of the annual appropriations process.  The Executive Branch can circumvent Congress’ power of the purse, a safeguard that’s been part of our political tradition since the Magna Carta.</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		

		

		

	</td>
