	<tr>
		<td class="alt2" style="border:1px inset">
			
				<div>
					Originally Posted by <strong>Torcer Arcana</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1459266#post1459266" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost.gif" border="0" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div style="font-style:italic">Possibly, but it&#8217;s a criticism without a context.  The all important question is what the Government does with its control.  It&#8217;s not as if the problems go away the moment the Government takes control.  The Treasury Secretary doesn&#8217;t exactly inspire confidence the that he knows how to fix the potential insolvency and toxic asset problem, nor does the President.  <b>My great fear is that the Democrats will wield their control with the aim of political advantage rather than financial solvency considerations.</b></div>
			
		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>
</div>I'm always amazed at the level of paranoia in the U.S. about the intentions and actions of government (at all levels).  I'm somewhat curious as to the basis for it:<br />
 - has it been handed down since the origin of the Republic?<br />
 - is it a by-product of a two-party system (wider policy swings / more partisanship than under a multi-party system)?<br />
 - is it a remnant of the anti-Soviet propaganda of the 80s, painting any government action as &quot;socialist/communist&quot;?<br />
 - does it actually have a legitimate basis?  Is &quot;government&quot; in America significantly more corrupt than in other countries, and if so, why?<br />
<br />
Don't get me wrong - I know there is corruption in all organizations, including governments, all over the world.  But people don't seem to be nearly as pessimistic/cynical about their governments elsewhere as they are in the U.S., and I'm very curious as to why that is so.</div>
		<!-- / message -->

		

		

		

		

		

